node.text:
"We have two guardians: the jungle and the sea. If you don’t get eaten by sharks or your bones picked clean by ants, you will soon beg to return."⁠
⁠
From 1852 to 1953, France’s Caribbean penal colony on Devil's Island was the most feared prison in the world. But when new inmates first arrived, they were shocked to find that there were few guards and that they were welcome to try to escape at any time. Many tried, but only a few succeeded. ⁠
⁠
The waters around the island were teeming with sharks and nearly unnavigable because of strong currents. And if prisoners tried to head the other direction and run into the jungle, they would be faced with the horrors of flesh-eating ants, skin-boring insects, and a host of deadly infections. Nearly everyone who tried to escape was never seen again or otherwise voluntarily came back to the prison — where they’d shortly be dead anyway. Go inside France’s infamous island prison by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠

node.text:
"Our ancestors saw wetlands as mystical places where they could connect with their gods and the Otherworld."⁠
⁠
A 1,600-year-old find in central Ireland is giving archaeologists a glimpse into the country's eerie pagan past. While combing a bog in advance of a road-building project, they unearthed an eight-foot wooden totem with a human-shaped head at the top — and both animal remains and a "ritual dagger" nearby. The dagger had never been used to cut meat or wood, and so archaeologists believe it was used to sacrifice animals in order to commune with the gods of the "Otherworld." Go inside this remarkable find by following the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
In 1971, a mysterious man known as D.B. Cooper hijacked a plane to steal $200K — then disappeared via parachute. Though he left behind his clip-on tie, a tie clip, and eight cigarette butts, his DNA sample yielded no helpful clues. Authorities said, "We originally thought Cooper was an experienced jumper, perhaps even a paratrooper. We concluded after a few years this was simply not true. No experienced parachutist would have jumped in the pitch-black night, in the rain, with a 200-mile-an-hour wind in his face, wearing loafers and a trench coat."⁠
⁠
The FBI not only failed to find out who he was, they also had no clue where he went or why he wanted the money in the first place. They didn't even know if he survived his fall.⁠
⁠
But nine years after the skyjacking, an 8-year-old boy discovered $5,880 of the stolen money on the shore of the Columbia River near Portland. To this day, it remains the sole piece of verifiable evidence linked to the case that was found outside of the plane. Dive into this maddening unsolved mystery — and all the craziest theories it's inspired — by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

Though the 100-million-year-old alligator gar once lived all over the world, you can only find it in North and Central America today — with just Texas and Louisiana maintaining stable populations. While the species is not considered endangered, many conservationists are concerned about the future of this prehistoric creature. Famous for his 1981 hit single "Super Freak," Rick James lived an even wilder lifestyle than his music implied. From dabbling in a life of crime as a pimp and burglar to indulging in drug binges and sex parties, it seemed like the King of Punk-Funk was willing to try just about anything once. But after his beloved mother died of cancer in 1991, his life spiraled further out of control than ever before. As James recalled, "There was nothing to keep me from descending into the lowest level of Hell. That meant orgies. That meant sadomasochism. That even meant bestiality. I was the Roman emperor Caligula. I was the Marquis de Sade."⁠
⁠
Take a closer look at the incredible rise and tragic demise of Rick James by clicking the link in our profile.⁠

node.text:
Perhaps no survivor of the Titanic was more fearless than "The Unsinkable Molly Brown." Famously portrayed in the classic 1997 film, Brown was even more formidable in real life. When the ship began to sink on the night of April 14, 1912, Brown sprang into action, tirelessly helping others board lifeboats before she was finally persuaded to board one herself. Once aboard, she grabbed an oar and rowed her fellow passengers toward safety — before stopping to insist that the vessel's crewman turn around so that they could save more people. When he told her that they could be sucked into the frozen depths of the North Atlantic, she refused to back down and threatened to toss him overboard if he didn't turn back.⁠
⁠
From the real-life stories behind the movie to the astounding tales that were left out of your history textbooks, explore more about the Titanic by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
On the morning of July 20, 2001, Andrea Yates waited for her husband to leave for work before feeding her five children breakfast and then systematically drowning them in the family bathtub one by one.⁠
⁠
She started with her two-year-old, Luke, followed by three-year-old Paul and five-year-old John. After killing each one, she took them to her bedroom and laid them on the bed. Then she came for six-month-old Mary, who she left floating in the tub afterward. Finally, she took seven-year-old Noah to the bathroom. When he saw his newborn sister in the water, the terrified boy tried to run away — but his mother quickly caught him and claimed her final victim. Leaving Noah in the bathtub, she took Mary out of the water and placed her in the arms of John on the bed, then gently tucked them all in with a blanket. Her plan now complete, she called the police and waited to be arrested.⁠
⁠
Follow the link in our bio to go inside the shocking murders by Andrea Yates and the Christian extremism and postpartum psychosis behind this disturbing case.⁠
⁠

node.text:
Beheading and burning at the stake are some of the most infamous execution methods of the Middle Ages — but did you know that some victims were condemned to "death by elephant"?⁠
⁠
Most commonly used in Southeast Asia, death by elephant was a very popular way to kill prisoners since authorities could train the animals to torture people in specific ways before killing them — such as crushing their limbs before smashing their head. While one might assume that death by tiger or lion would make more sense, the executioner had far more control over an elephant. And thus, they could determine exactly when and how they wanted the person to die — making it one of the most brutal ways to go.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in our bio for more Medieval execution methods that are the definition of cruel and unusual.⁠
⁠

node.text:
In 1968, researchers in Finland discovered a mysterious Viking grave dating back 1,000 years. The grave contained the remains of a person presumed to have been a warrior, complete with two swords. But this person was also dressed in women’s clothing, leading researchers to believe that the grave held a female warrior — or that it once contained both a man and a woman.⁠
⁠
But new DNA analysis has shown that both of these conclusions were incorrect and that the grave actually contained the remains of one intersex person who possessed an extra X chromosome. This recent find sheds incredible new light on gender expression and acceptance in Viking society. Go inside this incredible find by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#viking #vikinghistory #worldhistory #europeanhistory #historyuncovered

node.text:
From his bizarre life as a Siberian mystic to his brutal death at the hands of assassins, Grigori Rasputin was the most infamous figure in Tsarist Russia. Revered by some as a prophet and derided by others as a charlatan, Rasputin used his wit to charm his way into the court of Nicholas II, the last emperor of Russia. While it's unclear exactly how much influence he had over matters of state, we do know that he had enough power to make other nobles feel threatened — and grow determined to end his life. ⁠
⁠
But by killing him, his assassins not only eliminated their enemy but may have also unwittingly altered world history forever. Just before his death in 1916, Rasputin was apparently trying to negotiate peace with Germany. If he had succeeded, the Kerensky Coup and Bolshevik Revolution probably wouldn't have happened. There would have been no civil war, no Stalin, and maybe even no World War II.⁠
⁠
Discover the bizarre story of Rasputin's life — and his even stranger death — by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
